# Plan: Working with the Bangsamoro Government — A Guide for Fresh Graduates and Job Seekers

**Date**: 2026-03-26 (revised)
**Status**: PLANNED (execute next session)
**Guidebook #**: 13 in the series (first public-facing guidebook)
**Tier**: Comprehensive (19 chapters, 350-400 pages)

---

## What Makes This Guidebook Different

All previous guidebooks are **internal** — for people already inside BARMM government. This guidebook is **external** — for people who want to **join**. The reader may not know what "BTA" stands for.

### Voice

| Previous guidebooks | This guidebook |
|---|---|
| Coaching a peer | Welcoming a newcomer |
| Assumes government literacy | Assumes zero government experience |
| Imperative ("Draft the briefer") | Invitational ("Here's what the job involves") |

---

## Part I: Understanding the Bangsamoro Government (Chapters 1-5)

Before you apply, understand what you're joining. These 5 chapters give you the foundation.

### Chapter 1 — Why the Bangsamoro Government Needs You

**Opening**: Start with the development gap and the opportunity — not history.

- The BDP 2023-2028 has 6 goals and needs thousands of competent staff
- What makes BARMM different: autonomous governance, moral governance, Islamic values
- The transition period: building a government from the ground up (you get to be a founder)
- What "public service" means in the Bangsamoro context — not just a job, a calling
- The 12-point priority agenda and where staff are needed most

### Chapter 2 — The Bangsamoro Story: From Struggle to Self-Governance

**Opening**: "You are joining a government that was born from a peace agreement. That history shapes everything."

- **The Bangsamoro struggle** — brief, dignified history (not a textbook — a narrative)
  - The Moro identity and the centuries of resistance
  - ARMM and why it failed
  - The peace process: GRP-MILF, Framework Agreement, Comprehensive Agreement on the Bangsamoro (CAB)
- **The Bangsamoro Organic Law (RA 11054)** — what it IS and what it MEANS
  - What the BOL established: autonomous government with real powers
  - The 2019 plebiscite: the Bangsamoro people chose this
  - Territory: 5 provinces + Cotabato City + 63 barangays in North Cotabato (BOL Art. III)
- **Key BOL provisions every government worker should know**:
  - Article IV: Powers of the Bangsamoro Government (what BARMM can do that other regions cannot)
  - Article V, Section 2: Enumerated powers (55 areas of competence)
  - Article X: Shari'ah justice system (unique to BARMM)
  - Article XII: Fiscal autonomy (block grant, revenue powers)
  - Article XIV: The Bangsamoro Parliament
- **The transition period** — what it means that the BTA is transitional (2019-2025, extended)
  - Regular elections and the shift from appointed to elected government
  - Why the transition creates both urgency and opportunity for new staff

### Chapter 3 — How the Government Is Organized: BAA 13 and the Administrative Code

**Opening**: "BAA 13 is the blueprint. Learn it the way an architect learns a floor plan."

- **What BAA 13 (Bangsamoro Administrative Code) does** — defines the structure, powers, and functions of every ministry, office, and agency
- **The Parliament (BTA)**
  - 80 Members of Parliament, the Speaker, the Secretary General
  - Committees and their jurisdictions
  - The Secretariat and parliamentary offices
  - Parliamentary staff roles (PAO, LSO, PIMAO)
- **The Chief Minister and Cabinet**
  - Executive function, ministerial appointments, Cabinet meetings
- **The 16 Ministries** — name, mandate (from BAA 13), enabling BAAs:

| Ministry | BAA 13 Mandate | Key Enabling BAAs |
|---|---|---|
| MBHTE (Education) | Comprehensive education system | BAA 18 (Education Code) |
| MOH (Health) | Health service delivery | — |
| MAFAR (Agriculture) | Agricultural development | — |
| MILG (Interior & Local Government) | LGU coordination | BAA 49 (Bangsamoro Local Governance Code) |
| MPWH (Public Works) | Infrastructure | — |
| MENRE (Environment) | Natural resources | — |
| MSSD (Social Services) | Social welfare | — |
| MOTC (Transportation) | Transportation networks | — |
| MFBM (Finance, Budget, Management) | Fiscal management | BAA 84 (Budget System Act) |
| MOL (Labor) | Employment, labor standards | BAA 82 (Labor Code) |
| MST (Science & Technology) | Innovation, research | — |
| MTIT (Trade, Investment, Tourism) | Economic development | — |

- **Key Offices and Agencies** — created by specific BAAs:
  - BWC (Bangsamoro Women Commission) — BAA 8
  - BHRC (Human Rights Commission) — BAA 9
  - BYC (Bangsamoro Youth Commission) — BAA 10
  - BPDA (Planning and Development Authority)
  - OOBC (Office for Other Bangsamoro Communities)
  - BEDC (Economic Development Council)
- **Local Government Units** — 5 provinces, 116 municipalities, 2,590 barangays
  - **BAA 49 (Bangsamoro Local Governance Code)** — the enabling law for all LGUs under BARMM
  - How LGU structure differs from national LGC (RA 7160)
  - Provincial, municipal, and barangay government positions
- **How to read BAA 13** — the mandate section, the powers section, the organizational structure section. Where to find your prospective office's legal basis.

### Chapter 4 — Your Employment Framework: The Bangsamoro Civil Service Code (BAA 17)

**Opening**: "BAA 17 governs your hiring, your evaluation, your promotion, and your dismissal. Know it."

- **What BAA 17 covers** — the complete employment framework for BARMM government workers
- **The merit and fitness principle** — how it works in practice (competitive selection, not patronage)
- **Types of appointments**:
  - Permanent (plantilla) — security of tenure, full benefits
  - Temporary — specified period, renewable
  - Coterminous — tied to the appointing authority's term
  - Contractual — Contract of Service (COS), Job Order (JO)
  - Casual — seasonal or intermittent work
- **Qualification standards** — education, experience, training, eligibility requirements per position
- **The CSC and BARMM** — how the national Civil Service Commission relates to BARMM's civil service
  - CSC eligibility remains the national standard
  - BARMM can create its own qualification standards within CSC framework
- **Performance management** — Strategic Performance Management System (SPMS)
  - Individual Performance Commitment and Review (IPCR)
  - Office Performance Commitment and Review (OPCR)
  - Rating period, target-setting, mid-year review, year-end evaluation
- **Rewards and recognition** — Program on Awards and Incentives for Service Excellence (PRAISE)
  - Performance-Based Bonus (PBB)
  - Step increment, loyalty award, length of service
- **Discipline** — Rules on Administrative Cases in the Civil Service (RRACCS)
  - Grounds for disciplinary action
  - Due process requirements
  - Penalties (reprimand → suspension → dismissal)
- **Leave benefits** — vacation, sick, maternity/paternity, solo parent, study, special
- **Government systems and compliance**:
  - SPMS (Strategic Performance Management System) — the backbone of government accountability
  - SALN — annual asset declaration (constitutional requirement)
  - OHRAORA — attendance and timekeeping
  - ARTA compliance — Citizen's Charter and service standards
  - Government benefits administration — GSIS, PhilHealth, Pag-IBIG enrollment
- **The Code of Conduct** — RA 6713 norms as applied in BARMM + moral governance overlay
- **Other key civil service issuances**:
  - CSC MC No. 14/2018 — Omnibus Rules on Appointments
  - CSC RRACCS (Revised Rules on Administrative Cases) — disciplinary framework
  - CSC MC No. 72/2019 and MC No. 2/2022 — Complete Staff Work requirements
  - Executive Order on government working hours and flexible work arrangements

### Chapter 5 — The Bangsamoro Development Plan: What You're Working Toward

**Opening**: "Every memo you write, every briefer you draft, every program you implement serves one plan. Know it."

- **What the BDP is** — the 2nd Bangsamoro Development Plan (2023-2028), the government's roadmap
- **The Overall Goal**: An empowered, cohesive, and progressive Bangsamoro
- **The Vision**: "A Bangsamoro that is united, enlightened, self-governing, peaceful, just, morally upright, and progressive."
- **The 6 Development Goals** (what your work contributes to):
  1. Stable, Just, and Accountable Government
  2. Equitable, Competitive, and Robust Economy
  3. Peaceful, Safe, and Resilient Communities
  4. Inclusive, Responsive, and Quality Social Services
  5. Rich and Diverse Bangsamoro Culture and Identity
  6. Strategic, Adequate, and Climate-Resilient Infrastructure
- **The 8 Development Strategies** — how goals become action
- **The 12 Pillars of Moral Governance** — the ethical foundation (integrity, accountability, transparency, patriotism, excellence, cultural understanding, loyalty to God, justice, inclusivity, objectivity, dialogue, balance)
- **Macroeconomic targets** — the numbers your work is measured against (GRDP 8-9%, poverty 20-25% by 2028, unemployment 3-5%)
- **How to connect YOUR work to the BDP**:
  - Every MOA maps to at least one BDP goal
  - Every IPCR should reference BDP alignment
  - Every policy recommendation should cite the relevant BDP chapter
  - Every budget proposal justifies spending against BDP targets
- **The Enhanced 12-Point Priority Agenda** — the Chief Minister's implementation priorities within the BDP
- **Where to read the full BDP** — 14 chapters, available at BPDA website and BARMM Official Gazette

### Chapter 6 — Choosing Your Path: Parliament vs. Ministry vs. Office vs. LGU

**Opening**: "BARMM has four career tracks. Each leads somewhere different. Choose wisely."

| Track | What you'll do daily | Key competencies | Entry positions | Career ceiling |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Parliament** | Draft bills, write briefers, prepare speeches, support committees | Investigation, policy analysis, legal competence, CSW | Legislative Staff Officer I (SG 11) | SLSO I → Legislative Chief → Director |
| **Ministry** | Implement programs, deliver services, manage budgets, write policy | Technical expertise, project management, budget analysis | Administrative Officer/Analyst (SG 11-15) | Staff → Division Chief → Director → Undersecretary |
| **Office/Agency** | Focused mandate (youth, women, planning, economic development) | Stakeholder engagement, program design, M&E | Project Officer/Specialist (SG 11-15) | Staff → Section Head → Executive Director |
| **LGU** | Frontline service delivery, community engagement, local governance | Community relations, compliance, operations | Municipal Staff (SG 8-11) | Staff → Department Head → Administrator |

- **How to decide**: Interest assessment questions
- **Switching tracks** — is it possible? (Yes — through transfer, detailing, or reapplication)
- **The generalist vs. specialist question** — do you want breadth or depth?

