## Part III: Succeeding in Government (Chapters 9-15)

### Chapter 9 — How Work Gets Done: Complete Staff Work

**Opening**: "Every assignment you receive will follow this process. Learn it now."

- **What CSW is** — the decision-maker should only need to approve or disapprove
- **The ADDRESS IT Process** (7 steps — explained for beginners):
  - **A**nalyze the Context — understand the assignment
  - **D**efine and **D**eliberate — what's the problem?
  - **R**esearch — gather information
  - **E**xplore — generate and evaluate options
  - **S**ubmit — write the proposal/report
  - **S**ustain — implement the solution
  - **I**terate and improve — learn and adjust
- **CSW types you'll encounter**: legislative briefer, budget briefer, policy recommendation, project proposal, legal opinion, general CSW
- **The transmittal memorandum** — how your work gets from your desk to the decision-maker
- **What "completed" means** — supervisor clearance, quality check, no loose ends
- **CSW quick reference card** (same as CSW Guidebook Appendix A — cross-reference)

### Chapter 10 — Competencies of a Bangsamoro Government Worker

**Opening**: "Your degree got you in the door. Your competencies determine how far you go."

- **What competencies are** (CSC definition: KSAs demonstrated through observable behaviors)
- **Core Competencies** (from CSC Competency Dictionary, customized for BARMM):
  - Integrity and Ethics (+ amanah, moral governance)
  - Professionalism and Service Orientation (+ Bangsamoro cultural sensitivity)
  - Teamwork and Collaboration (+ shura)
  - Results Orientation (+ BDP goal alignment)
  - Communication (+ multilingual context)
- **The Bangsamoro Dimension** — competencies NOT in the CSC Dictionary:
  - BOL Literacy
  - Bangsamoro Cultural Competence (13 ethnolinguistic groups)
  - Complete Staff Work (ADDRESS IT)
  - Moral Governance Practice
  - Peace Process Awareness
- **Functional Competencies by Track** (Parliament: PAO/LSO/PIMAO; Ministry: technical/admin; Office: program/specialist)
- **How competencies are assessed** (hiring CBI, probation, SPMS annual, promotion)
- **Self-Assessment Worksheet** — rate yourself, identify gaps, plan development

### Chapter 11 — Working with Your Supervisor

**Opening**: "Your supervisor's job is to develop you. Your job is to make that possible."

- **What your supervisor expects** (from the staff's perspective):
  - Come to check-ins prepared (progress, blockers, questions)
  - Receive feedback without defensiveness (the SBI model — what it sounds like from your end)
  - Take ownership of your development (don't wait to be coached)
  - Produce CSW that doesn't need rework
- **The check-in rhythm** — what monthly check-ins look like (4-step protocol — your role)
- **How you're being assessed** — the PPR framework (Performance, Potential, Readiness):
  - Low performance → your supervisor will coach for behavior change
  - High performance / low potential → you'll be kept engaged but developed differently
  - High performance / high potential → you'll be stretched with bigger assignments
- **How to receive feedback** — the SBI model from the receiving end
  - When your supervisor says "In yesterday's meeting [S], you didn't present the options analysis [B], which meant the committee couldn't make a decision [I]" — here's what to do
- **Your performance evaluation** — how the 6-step evaluation protocol works (what the supervisor is doing, what you should prepare)
- **When things go wrong** — what a PIP (Performance Improvement Plan) means, progressive discipline, your rights

### Chapter 12 — Government Communication: Writing That Gets Read

**Opening**: "In government, writing IS working. If you can't write a proper memo, you can't do the job."

- **The memo** — format, tone, structure (To, From, Date, Subject, body, action requested)
- **The transmittal memorandum** — when and how to use it (connects to CSW Chapter 9)
- **Endorsements** — "1st Endorsement," "2nd Endorsement," routing and referral
- **Email in government** — formal but efficient, CC/BCC rules, response expectations, "Noted" vs. "Approved" vs. "For compliance"
- **Meeting minutes** — format, action items, distribution
- **The letter** — official correspondence format for BARMM entities
- **Government writing voice** — clear, concise, no jargon (apply BARMM guidebook voice)
- **Common writing mistakes** — "Respectfully submitted" vs. "Respectfully transmitted," "thru" vs. "through," "the undersigned" (just say "I")

### Chapter 13 — The Bangsamoro Government Employee Journey

**Opening**: "Your career is a journey with defined stages. Know what's coming at each one."

This chapter maps the **complete employee lifecycle** from BAA 17 (Bangsamoro Civil Service Code), so you can see the full path from application to retirement.

**13.1 The Journey Map** (visual overview):

```
APPLY → HIRE → ONBOARD → PROBATION → PERFORM → DEVELOP → PROMOTE → LEAD → TRANSITION
```

| Stage | Duration | What happens | Key milestone |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Apply** | 1-3 months | Job search, PDS, interview, comparative assessment | Appointment letter |
| **Onboard** | Days 1-30 | Oath, ID, orientation, office tour, MOP review, system access | Completed orientation checklist |
| **Probation** | Months 1-6 | Learning the job, first CSW assignments, supervisor check-ins | Probationary evaluation PASSED |
| **Perform** | Years 1-3 | IPCR targets, regular CSW output, SPMS ratings, training | First "Very Satisfactory" or higher rating |
| **Develop** | Years 2-5 | Functional training, CSW mastery, lateral assignments, graduate studies | Competency proficiency across core areas |
| **Promote** | Year 3+ | Next-in-rank, competitive selection, salary grade advancement | First promotion |
| **Lead** | Year 5+ | Supervisory role, team management, system design, mentoring | First supervisory appointment |
| **Transition** | Varies | Transfer, secondment, retirement, resignation, or new career | Graceful exit with knowledge transfer |

**13.2 Onboarding: Your First 30 Days** (from BAA 17 + BARMM practice):
- **Day 1**: Report to HR, oath of office, government ID processing, IT system access
- **Day 1-3**: Office orientation — meet your supervisor, receive your position description, get office tour
- **Week 1**: Read the MOP (if it exists), understand the org chart, learn the filing system, attend your first staff meeting
- **Week 1-2**: First supervisor check-in — expectations, first assignments, communication preferences
- **Week 2-4**: Complete first CSW assignment using ADDRESS IT, attend government orientation seminar (if scheduled)
- **By Day 30**: Know your office mandate (from BAA 13), know your supervisor's expectations, know the approval workflow, have submitted at least one completed staff work

**13.3 Probation: Months 1-6**
- What's being evaluated (results + behaviors against your position description)
- The probationary evaluation form — what your supervisor fills out
- What "satisfactory" means — and what happens if you don't meet it
- How to ask for help without looking incompetent
- The most common reasons probation fails (and how to avoid them)

**13.4 Civil Service Systems You Must Know**

Every BARMM civil servant interacts with these systems. Learn them in your first month:

- **SPMS (Strategic Performance Management System)** — the official CSC performance management framework
  - IPCR (Individual Performance Commitment and Review) — YOUR performance contract
  - OPCR (Office Performance Commitment and Review) — your office's performance contract
  - The annual cycle: target-setting (January) → mid-year review (July) → year-end evaluation (December)
  - The 5-point scale: Poor (1) → Unsatisfactory (2) → Satisfactory (3) → Very Satisfactory (4) → Outstanding (5)
  - Your SPMS rating determines: PBB eligibility, promotion ranking, training priority, step increment
- **CSC Online Systems**:
  - OHRAORA (Omnibus Hours Rendering and Attendance / Online Registration of Attendance) — digital timekeeping
  - ARTA Citizen's Charter — every office must have service standards posted
  - GSIS Portal — retirement, insurance, loan systems
  - PhilHealth Member Portal — health insurance
  - Pag-IBIG Fund Portal — housing loan, savings
- **SALN (Statement of Assets, Liabilities, and Net Worth)** — mandatory annual filing (deadline: April 30)
- **PDS (Personal Data Sheet / CS Form 212)** — keep it updated; required for every promotion and transfer
- **Leave management** — vacation leave (15 days), sick leave (15 days), how to file, force leave, monetization
- **PRAISE (Program on Awards and Incentives for Service Excellence)** — how recognition works
- **Performance-Based Bonus (PBB)** — requires office to meet OPCR targets AND individual to meet IPCR

**13.5 Cultural Navigation**
- Prayer times and prayer rooms — every BARMM office provides space
- Ramadan — adjusted work hours, iftar etiquette, respect for fasting colleagues
- Eid al-Fitr and Eid al-Adha — office closures, greetings, celebrations
- Bangsamoro hospitality — food sharing, respect for elders, honorifics
- Working across ethnolinguistic groups — Meranaw, Maguindanaon, Tausug, Sama, Yakan and others
- "I'm not Muslim" — your place in a Muslim-majority workplace (respect, inclusion, boundaries)

**13.6 Ten Mistakes New Staff Make**
1. Not reading the BOL (you work for an autonomous government — know the law that created it)
2. Assuming national government rules apply (BARMM has its own civil service, budget, and administrative codes)
3. Not learning the office's approval workflow (every output follows a chain — learn it Day 1)
4. Waiting to be told what to do (government rewards initiative — propose, don't just wait)
5. Submitting incomplete CSW (the "completed" in CSW means COMPLETED — no loose ends)
6. Not knowing your supervisor's communication style (some want daily updates, some want weekly — ask)
7. Avoiding the cultural context (you're in Bangsamoro — learn the greetings, respect the traditions)
8. Skipping training opportunities (every training builds your competency profile for promotion)
9. Not connecting work to BDP goals (your IPCR should reference the development plan)
10. Thinking this is just a job (it's the implementation of a peace agreement — treat it accordingly)

### Chapter 14 — Career Growth and Development

- Promotion mechanics (next-in-rank, competitive selection, merit)
- The 3 competency frameworks you'll encounter:
  - Parliament Staff Competencies (25) — if you work in Parliament
  - ACSCCRaPATFEE (12) — for CSW practitioners (everyone)
  - 12 Supervisory Competencies — when you become a supervisor
- Training: CSW training (ADDRESS IT), supervisory development, functional skills
- Graduate studies and scholarships
- Lateral movement, detailing, secondment
- The path to leadership (staff → supervisor → director)

### Chapter 15 — The Bangsamoro Public Servant

**Opening**: "This chapter is about who you become, not what you do."

- **Moral governance** — the 12 pillars in daily practice
- **Islamic leadership principles** — amanah, adl, shura, rahmah, sidq
- **Serving diverse communities** — 13 ethnolinguistic groups, OBCs, indigenous peoples
- **Your legal obligations**:
  - RA 6713 (Code of Conduct) — the 8 norms
  - SALN (Statement of Assets, Liabilities, Net Worth) — annual filing requirement
  - Anti-Graft (RA 3019) — what counts, what to refuse, what to report
  - COA audit compliance
  - Conflict of interest rules
  - Whistleblower protections
- **The peace process and your role** — you are implementing the peace that others fought for
- **Why this work matters** — connecting your daily tasks to BDP goals and the aspirations of the Bangsamoro people

